HTML Injection is a type of attack where an attacker injects malicious HTML code into a web page,This occurs when a web application fails to properly validate or sanitize user input and directly embeds that input into the HTML content of the page.
As a result, the injected HTML is rendered by the victim’s browser, potentially altering the page structure or displaying unauthorized content.



                                                                                      Types of HTML Injection



1.Reflected HTML Injection
Test Scenario: A search box or URL parameter reflects user input directly in the response.
Example URL:https://example.com/search?q=<h1>HTML-Test</h1>


2.Stored HTML Injection
Test Scenario:A comment, feedback, or profile field where input is saved in a database


1.Submit the payload in a persistent input field
  <b>Stored-HTML</b>

2.Save or submit the form

3.refresh page on browser

4.Revisit the page where the input is displayed



                                                                           Input Points Vulnerable to HTML Injection


Search Bars
Contact Forms
Comment Sections
User Registration Forms
Login Forms (error messages / username reflection)
Feedback Forms
Product Reviews
Chat Boxes / Messaging Features
Newsletter Signup Forms
Profile Information (bio, display name, status)
Support / Ticket Systems
Order Notes / Special Instructions
URL Parameters & Query Strings
File Metadata Fields (file name, description)
Survey & Poll Forms
Referral / Coupon Fields etc...




